title: Structur3D Discov3ry Paste Extruder Tip Mount For Printrbot

description.text: Thing to mount your Structur3D Discov3ry paste extruder tip to a Printrbot Metal Simple or Printrbot Metal Plus printer. This thing is designed to be super adjustable. By allowing adjustment, you can move your paste extruder mount up and down respectively when not in use and while in use so your Printrbot can print plastic filament as well as pastes from the Discov3ry without removing your paste mount.

The thing is comprised of three 3D printed parts.

I printed on my Printrbot Plus Metal, using Simplify3D v2.2, and used a .2mm layer height, 4 solid layers for the top/bottom and side shells, 25% infill, 210 degrees Celsius using Printrbot PLA filament (at high-end for temp for PLA to get a good bond between layers), and support and a raft enabled for printing the mount body as I printed on its side for vertical layer "grain". The clip and shim were printed flat on print bed without support or a raft.

  • For use on a Printrbot Metal Plus, you only need to print the 1) mount body and 2) clip
  • For use on a Printrbot Metal Simple, you need to print the 1) mount body, 2) clip and 3) shim

The clip is screwed into mount body using 6-32 x 1/2" machine screws available from any hardware store. The Structur3D Discov3ry extruder paste tip or extruder paste tube is clamped between printed clip and printed mount body.

This thing is connected to Printrbot Metal Simple and Printrbot Metal Plus by using longer M3 screws and washers and existing Printrbot aluminum extruder M3 screw holes. These M3 screws and washers can be purchased online or from any small hardware store in the US. The long M3 screws go through the long open slots on the mount body and when loosened, allow the mount be lowered and raised.

The shim is only used for the Printrbot Simple Metal and is mounted between the Printrbot aluminum extruder and the mount body. The oversized shim holes have the M3 screws pass through them.

I have a blog post that includes additional details regarding this thing and its use with the Structur3D Discov3ry paste extruder.

Got a Printrbot Simple but it needs a knob to turn the z-axis up and down for zeroing. It had to be something small, because there's not a lot of clearance around the screw on such a small machine. So here's a little knob that screws on the top! Should also fit any other 8mm threaded rods. The hole in the center is 6.75mm, suitable for tapping to M8x1.25, but you want the knob to bind in place around the shaft -- so just hold the shaft with vise-grips and carefully thread the knob on with moderate force. I went about a quarter inch down and haven't had any slippage. UPDATE
While the original version fits on a stock, properly-assembled Simple, the clearance between the edge of the knob and the rear vertical rod may be a little close if you have significant Z-wobble at the top. In this case, download the slightly smaller version instead for a little extra clearance. UPDATE 2
I've printed and tested both knobs, and the smaller one works better with no clearance or handling issues, so I've removed the larger one.
Printed on the Simple at 0.3mm layer height, 0.3 rectilinear infill, 3 shells, PLA. 3 shells are important to ensure you don't crack through into the infill when threading the rod into place.

title: Laser holder for the Silhouette Portrait cutter (might work in the Cameo as well)

description.text:
This is my first iteration of a custom holder for the Silhouette Portrait which allows you to use a cutting/burning laser diode module in place of the knife cutter.

The tab on the side is used to mount a switch which is pressed when the Silhouette moves the pen down (cutting.) This switch is connected between the laser power source to turn the laser on when the portrait doing a cut move and off when the pen is up.

I plan to improve this significantly and would welcome any help. See the instructions tab for some important information to help in this regard.

I have included the Sketchup file so it can be modified/adapted easily. If you derive a design from this, please let me know so we can work together.

Designed for a 12mm diameter laser module. Can be easily adapted for 9mm diode modules.

Currently 500W is probably the max power safe to use since the current design doesn't allow for a heatsink. I have a 3W diode, so I am planning to improve the design to allow some type of heat-sinking/active-cooling for the laser. Most laser modules have a max temperature of 45-50c before they will start to fail. Well below the melting point of PLA or ABS. Installing a temperature sensor inside the module and using that to compensate in your driving circuit is ideal. I will post a circuit when I get to it.

Most diode modules are designed to focus at 30mm (smallest beam diameter, max power) from the work piece. I have attempted to set the diode at the right height so that it will be 30mm from the work surface when the pen is down. This will need some tweaking.

Currently, it is not possible to adjust the lens once in the holder. So it will need to be focused and threadlocked outside of the holder. One improvement I am planning is to allow focusing (to account for various thicknesses of material) while in the holder. Suggestions appreciated.

The mount for the switch could be improved. It is just blank at the moment. You will need to determine how to mount your switch on your own. We want the switch to engage when the portrait clamp is at the very bottom. I am working to tweak this and lock it in with a particular recommended switch.

The plastic shroud around the portrait carriage snaps off easily, exposing the leads which drive the knife solenoid. I am looking at simple methods to interface directly to that instead of a switch. This would prevent the pen from moving up/down and the signal would be used to turn the laser on/off instead.

But I will likely keep the switch design as well since that is useful for those not wanting to mess with their stock portrait cutter.

So, improvements I am planning/could use some help with:

  1. Allow focusing of the laser lens while the module is installed.
  2. Improve switch mount and sources for the recommend switch
  3. Adding heatsink/Active-cooling into the design (bonus if it can blow the smoke away from the laser as well)

Watch here for additional reverse engineering information and specs.

A. The clamp on the portrait is 17mm tall
B. From the platen to the top of the clamp is 29mm when in the down position and 35mm in the up position (need these verified.)
C. Flat area to the left of the pen is 32mm from the platen
D. Flat area begins about .5mm forward of the centerline of the pen diameter
E. Pen diameter is 14mm
F. Flange of the pen is 17mm diameter
G. 19mm is the max diameter that will fit in the carriage for the back half

Side note: Another application I am investigating is PCB milling and/or etch resist printing.

description.text:
Within the last couple of weeks I've optimized and perfected the process of building scaled architecture models for real estate companies (see the images of an Ultimaker 2 based House). Within this process I (probably) developed a whole new way to print high mirrored surfaces with a kind-of-holographic-effect on it.

See my instructions to rebuild this effect for your own use and creativity.

PS: And sorry for not uploading the whole house model. I never share commisioned data.

The trick for this surface is to create a 3D model based on the used layer high of your printer. As this model was based on 0.15 mm on an Ultimaker 2, the two elements in this model (the plates and the solid cover) were 0.3 mm high which ends up with 4 layers after slicing.

Then the next trick is to rotate the model upside down so, that the final cover will get printed first on the (heated) glass plate of your printer. Using black PLA (InnoFil) will produce the best contrasted effect. Use a 0.0 first layer to get 100 % layer hight for all four layers and 60 °C bed heat / 210 °C Nozzle heat. Make sure your glass plate is cristal-clear without tape or glue and start your print without fans.

Due to the bed temperature the first two layers melt down and together with the solid cover part of the model but - and that's the base of this effect - the structure of these first two layers keeps alive and can get seen through the (semi-transparent) PLA layers.

To not damage the surface or brake this thin part you should wait until the glass plate is cold and the model releases by its own.

That's it. Turn your model and play around with the holographic effect under different light sources.

I call it the DORT-EFFECT! ;)

description.text:
This is a version of Ender Dragon by Intentional3D, published on Jul 14, 2014.

Initially I printed the model with the given files,but found problems with the assembly:

  • some parts broke easily (in particular the ball joints)
  • spent almost half a kilo of filament
  • too much time spent printing
  • too much time spent with the assembly
  • add to drill the tail and neck, and use a string, in order to keep it together.

So I´v made some changes to the model turning it more "printer friendly".

Less parts, Less post printing assembly.

Layer heigth - 0.2 mm
Print Speed - 50 mm/s (first layer 30%)
Perimeter, Top, Bottom - 4 layers
Infill - Honeycomb 20% (general parts)
Infill - Honeycomb 10% (body)

No need for support - some parts need small cuts after printed:

  • connections
  • top of neck and tail
  • cross on every vertebra (neck and tail)

Important features:
-The tail and neck are now printed in ONE piece. In the case of the tail there is the option to print in 2 parts (if the print area is less than 20cm)
-The legs (front and back) and the wings are printed already assembled. (just need to force them a litle)
-Tail, Neck and Wings are ready to insert a 2mm wire thru them in order to give them some stability.

WARNING:
Printing in a diferent scale will block or loosen parts the that are printed already assembled.

To give it steadiness you may need 2x 40cm 2mm wire (i used copper from electric wiring) to use along the tail/neck and left to right wings.

You should print individualy each of the front and back legs.

The Conrad Renkforce RF-1000 3D Printer has a tiny fan and a very massive extruder. I had a lot of issues with the small fan and decided to upgrade it with two 60mm Fans, so that the extruded filament can cool and doesn't get reheated a lot by the big extruder.
Please read the Instructions before printing!
If you have any suggestions on Improvement let me know in a comment :-)

Print the Parts either at Medium or high resolution (0.2mm or 0.1mm) with Raft and Support material. Infill min. 30% and 2 Shells.
You will need two 60 mm fans with a clip mount on them (screw hole thing will be uploaded soon). Now you can choose between 2 types of fan holders. Nr. 1 Has a seperation between the 2 fans and combines the airflow in the air channel. Nr. 2 does not have a seperation and combines the airflow in the fan holder. (Try out wich works best for you). The air channel is screwed with one screw on to the Renkforce extruder. The old small fan and holder need to be removed. Move the air channel in the slot and make sure that in the HOME position it doesn't touch the Metal parts of the Printer. Now just snap the fan holder into the air channel and you are good to go. I use an external PSU for the fans. They swich on with a relay that is connected to the old Fan connector of the Renkforce.
Just one last tip: The air channel has a support piece that prevents it from bending. It moves with the extruder in a Slot. To decrease friction Put some soft fabric (about 1mm thick) underneath it, wrap some tape around it and put a little grease in the slot.

title: R/C Bismarck and a waterpump yet

description.text:
Bismarck battleship

That will be an 1 metre long, bluetooth controlled model of the Bismarck battleship by german naval forces in 1939.

What are the planned features?

  • 1 metre length ✔
  • good printabillity
  • at least one artillery should be turnable and "shoot" water
  • bluetooth control with android smartphone
  • easy to build electronics
  • cheap as possible
     
  • print it once in a while?

These are just bad weeks for this challenges,

  • printer broke
  • car broke
  • son ill
  • and so on

because of that, the work on this project has been stopped untill i get my printer up and running again. Until yesterday i still had some hope to get the project done right on time for the MakeItFloat challenge.

What is finished so far?

  • waterpump
  • hull (printable, internal support)
  • not printable but modeled the upper part (bridge, artillery and so on) without the cranes

ToDo

  • easy electronics to rebuild at home
    • overall control with HC-05 (or alikes) bluetooth SPP + ATMega
    • write simple software for Android and ATMega or Arduino
    • motor control with simple MOSFET H-Bridge ✔
    • paddel control with cheap servo motor
  • upload layout, schematics for electronics (PCB)
  • write Android and ATMega/Arduino code (sadly the most easy part for me)
  • model carrier for electronics, motors and some kind of airsoft BB bearing for the turning artillery
  • make bridge (upper part) printable
  • write tutorials/HowTo's (compile app for Android, compile ATMega code, build electronics with single ATMega or Arduino, tricks to get the print up and running)

that's it so far. Since i've spend about 50 hours in my printer since last week and still wont get it to print reliably and anything else i could imagine breaks as well i can't tell when i will keep on this project.
For anyone interested in, i uploaded my project files as well. I wish any other competitor best luck!

One additional note
The parts for the waterpump are in the rsdoc files. I created many iterations depending on the power of your motor. Actually you need about 5,000+ rpm and the more torque you have, the bigger the lower part can be.

Hey guys!

Here we'd like to share with you the customized handle for Freaks3D - the most portable 3D printer in the world.

You can download any of the files to print and install on your Freaks3D, or if you haven't got a Freaks3D yet, hope these files help you with development of other gadgets or tools with practical use.

Allow us to do a short introduction of Freaks3D 3D printer.

It is a portable and usable 3D printer presented by ElecFreaks R&D team and has been live on Indiegogo from 14/07/2015 to 15/08/2015, starting at 259 USD.

Key features:

  1. Completely portable. The Freaks3D weighs 2.945kg and battery compatible. Small enough to blend in with any table but large enough to unleash your creativity.

  2. Simple structure. Extruded-aluminum beams to ensure sturdy and high-quality performance. The Freaks3D employs v-slot slider system to provide precise seamless positioning.

  3. Quality prints on your desktop. Detailed layer resolution at fast speed. All-metal nozzle head allows PLA/TPU filaments of a rainbow of colors without easy breaks or damage. No pre-heating is needed. Simply feed the filament into the entrance path and the printer will do the rest.

Details please visit http://igg.me/at/freaks3d.

Thanks for attention and help us spread the words to make 3D printing truly accessible for everyone.

title: Prusa i3 X-Carriage for GT2 belt

description.text:
There are a lot of very good X-Carriages out there with a lot of good features that I like but none of them got all of those on one X-Carriage.

I wanted a good hassle free and easy to use belt holder that is also small and compact such as the one from this carriage. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:840907

I wanted a big flat face that can take all different configurations of print heads. Single, dual, direct and bowden as I want to start experimenting with them. For that I also needed mounting holes that could accept fittings from 22mm up to 30 mm

The next requirement was a very sturdy but still compact bearing holder design that was capable to hold 4 LM8UU bearings as I might have some heavy payloads on it at some times.

Lastly I wanted a cable carrier support for my wiring as I want to install a semi permanent cable set on the printer that will be terminated at the carriage to enable plug and play print head replacement.

So I decided to draw up my own carriage that conform to my set of requirements.

What I still need to do is integrate an adjustable home sensor trigger for an Opto sensor as I have designed my new X Motor End with an integrated mount for the Opto sensor. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:922783

I can only do this when I have both the new carriage and motor end printed and installed on the printer so that I can get a good sense of what is needed,

So here it is, please comment if you can think of further enhancements for it.

Enjoy!

title: Hole resolution and calibration test DLP 3D printer

description.text:
This helps you find out the real projection resolution of your DLP 3D printer. It has holes and shafts from 50 microns until 18 mm of diameter. Also valid to calibrate the 3D printer.

To find out the therical projection resolution you just have to do this:

Y printing area/ projection pixels in Y axis
X printing area/ projection pixels in X axis

For example if you have a projector of 1920x1080 and a printing area of 16x9 cm your theorical printing resolution is:

160/1920=0.08333
90/1080=0.0833

So the theorical projection resolution is = 83.3 x 83.3 microns

Now you just have to print this test and see how different is the theory and the practice.

description.text:
Help with my next creation!
Having only found models on-line that were suitable for rendering, not printing, I decided to make my own!

Check out https://skfb.ly/F7Lv for a more controllable look of the city, you can even go first person and pretend you are flying a puddle jumper around! Video here Open link in new window/tab to skip straight to the item.

AtlantisCity is how I decided to put it together however if you head to Pinshape or shapetizer I have included the city's base and buildings as separate STL's so you can make your own layout! Each of the buildings has a different look from each side so you can re-use them just by rotating them and it will look like a different building. If you come up with your own building please message me :) The rules I used when designing them are:

  1. That they were hollow with internal chamfers to act like support material during print.
  2. The walls are a multiple of 0.4mm in thickness
  3. The overhangs are such that at a print resolution of 0.1mm with PLA there is no support material needed.
    I have included the most likely building to give you problems so you can do a test print before trying the whole thing :)
    It has all been designed with my FABtotum in mind so wall thickness's and overhangs are right for me but may not be for your printer. The main thing will be the wall thickness's, they are multiples of 0.4mm to go with my 0.35mm extruder.
    Check out the makes section to see my print.

Follow me on Twitter, Instagram and YouTube To keep apprised of new designs and my other projects.

description.text:
Update 2/26/2016. Thanks to DesignMakeTeach for pointing out that my original file had the equations incorrectly labeled. The correct version is now up: tetrahedron_1_2016.stl

This model is the tetrahedron defined by equations x+2y+z=2, x=2y, z=0, and x=0. The equations are printed on the model.

This model was designed and printed by my WLU summer research student Ryan McDonnell ('17). See http://mathvis.academic.wlu.edu/2015/07/14/tetrahedra/ for more information.

You may have to scale by a factor of 10 if you're using MakerWare, since it tends to import files in mm, not cm. Object is sized to be 10cm tall, but smaller prints should work just fine.

This object was made on a MakerBot2X. We used the following settings:
2 shells
0.20mm layer height
10% infill (hexagonal pattern)
No supports
raft off

We printed the object with the x+2y+z=2 face as the base. Thus, we needed to add some ABS juice to the build bed to be sure the object stuck and didn't curl up at the corners.
